caption: Photos by Pete Muller @pete_k_muller | After a sweltering day, the sun retreats and the temperature returns to comfortable. Weary residents of Stockholm emerge and the streets begin to hum. Relieved, I wander along the edge of Kungsträdgården park and find myself  drawn in by music. From a set of large speakers drift notes of "In the Mood," a classic swing tune by the composer Glenn Miller. In front of the speakers, smartly dressed men and women twirl together with skill and vivacity. They move in a style that harkens back to another time and place. On nearby benches, people eat ice cream and sip coffee. Children play in a fountain. The old watch the young and vice versa. In the generous hours of summer twilight, I wander the city streets. My grandfather left Sweden for the United States many years ago. I grew up singing Swedish songs and imagining what the place might be like. I traveled here for the first time this summer to attend a wedding. It left me with a clearer sense of the values and outlooks that were offered to me as a boy. Follow me pete_k_muller for more observations of our world.

caption:
Photos by Katie Orlinsky @katieorlinsky | The Batagaika Crater in the Siberian town of Batagay, Russia, is known as the "hell crater" to locals.  The crater is in fact a thermokarst depression, or permafrost “megaslump.” Found mainly in the Arctic, permafrost is the layer of continuously frozen soil that covers almost 1/4 of the Earth’s surface. Most permafrost areas have been frozen for more than 10,000 years and remain hidden underground. 
The Batagaika Crater, roughly half a mile long and 300 feet deep, is one of the exceptions. The crater started forming in the 1960s after nearby forests were cleared, exposing the permafrost to the sun. When permafrost laced with ice thaws, the ground collapses and forms craters and lakes. To this day the crater continues to grow. The ancient soils of Arctic permafrost, seen in the wall of the crater, hold the organic remains of leaves, grass, and animals that died thousands of years ago, during the Ice Age. All that carbon had been safely bound in frozen earth—until now. 
For nearly two years I've been working on “The Carbon Threat” for @natgeo (link in my bio @katieorlinsky): how Arctic permafrost is thawing much faster than expected, releasing carbon gases that could drastically speed up climate change. It is perhaps the least understood reason to hasten our transition off fossil fuels. Time is of the essence, and I hope our reporting can help the public and policymakers recognize this new, urgent reality.

caption: Photo by Beverly Joubert @beverlyjoubert | When we think of climate change and its impact on wildlife, we often don’t consider species as well adapted to hotter habitats as the African painted dog. But these animals are also sensitive to the changes taking place on our warming planet. Rising average temperatures mean fewer hours in the day are cool enough for the dogs to hunt, impacting their ability to find food and the survival rate of young pups. It’s one more added threat for a species already endangered by habitat loss, human-wildlife conflict, and disease. Climate change is here, its impacts are real and far-reaching–and it’s up to us to take action. #endangeredspecies #painteddog

caption: Photo by Renan Ozturk @renan_ozturk | Words by David Gonzalez: "Back at high camp. 8,300 meters. A place of shredded tents and wind-strewn garbage. The Earth’s highest dump, just below its highest cemetery. The rest of the team has gone on without me. I’m oddly at peace. Maybe it’s the satisfaction of doing something I never thought I’d do, in a place I never thought I’d see. Or maybe it’s the privilege I feel, to stand on the shoulder of the mother goddess of the mountains, and look out at the world. caption: Photo by Pete McBride @pedromcbride | Seeing Stripes: Botswana’s national animal, the zebra, migrates across the country twice a year. During the migrations, zebras and other wildlife started competing with cattle for limited water sources  after the Boteti River dried up. In 2009 high rainfall restored the river’s flow for the first time in 20 years, bringing much-needed relief to the area’s migratory animals. Botswana is one of 17 countries under extremely high water stress, like many regions facing imminent global water shortage. For more on conservation of wildlife and water, follow @pedromcbride. #zebras #Botswana #okavango #water #migration

caption: Photo by Babak Tafreshi @babaktafreshi | Far from city lights, there is unrivaled joy in stargazing and photography under a natural dark sky. The telephoto view reveals the tail of constellation Scorpius and two star clusters in the Milky Way. Appearing in this this single-exposure photograph is my friend Roger Craig Smith, renowned voice actor, and one of the many in the world who spend time under stars as their main hobby. Known as amateur astronomers, they can be of any age, from teenagers to seniors, from any profession, culture, and country. Some join together to form local astronomy clubs and some enjoy the solitude at dark. Some are general hobbyists with a pair of binoculars or a simple camera, and some are dedicated observers discovering new objects in the sky. What is shared by all of them is a respect for the dark skies and the natural night environment that we are losing to light pollution. See "Our nights are getting brighter, and Earth is paying the price" on natgeo.com for more and follow me @babaktafreshi for The World at Night photography. #saveournightsky #twanight #stargazing #astrophotography

caption: Photo by Keith Ladzinski @ladzinski | An aerial perspective of our boat cutting a line through an algae bloom of seemingly endless green. What you’re seeing here is a decades-old problem; the leading contributor of these blooms is excess phosphorus and nitrates from fertilizer used in large-scale agriculture that’s washed into streams as well as distributed via wind during the winter months. Through these tributary waterways, the chemicals eventually make their way into lakes. Pollutants from industrial and pharmaceutical factories are also a link; these chemicals and substances aren’t water soluble and over decades turn into what you’re seeing here. High temperatures and still air create the perfect conditions for algae to proliferate and accumulate at the surface. When temperatures increase, these blooms break out, which is unfortunately only increasing with the rise in temperatures directly correlated with climate change. It’s a serious problem, and one that is happening globally. To see more photos of this issue, please visit @ladzinski

caption: Photo by Joel Sartore @joelsartore | In order to move people to take action and save the planet, the Photo Ark uses eye contact, whenever possible. Much like this mandrill, we humans are primates too, and we rely on eye contact, along with body language, for 80% or more of our communication. At Team Photo Ark, our driving motto is this: As these species vanish, so could we. I had gone to Bioko Island in Equatorial Guinea to cover primate poaching. On one of my last days on the island, I went to a bush meat market, and found this juvenile mandrill chained to the rusting frame of an old car.  As a friend held up a black velvet cloth behind him, he reacted to seeing himself for the first time in the reflection of my lens filter. This animal was someone's pet, but there were laws on the books against keeping primates, so he could have been made into stew at any time if the price was right, especially being so close to the market. You can see more of my work by following me @joelsartore, and on view @SouthamptonArtsCenter co-presented by @ICP now through Sept. 8. #mandrill #PhotoArk #Savetogether

caption:
Photo by Ami Vitale @amivitale | Elephant keeper Lekupania gets a kiss from little Kapai on their daily nature walk at Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e). Having arrived so young, Kapai had a lot to learn about being an elephant, but she had the rest of the Reteti herd and her keepers to show her how to browse, graze, and navigate. Someday soon, she'll be big and strong, ready to return to the wild. Reteti Elephant Sanctuary is the first ever community-owned and -run elephant sanctuary in Africa. It provides a safe place for injured and orphaned elephant calves to heal so that they can be returned back to the wild. Reteti operates in partnership with Conservation International, which provides critical operational support and works to scale the community-centered model to create lasting impacts worldwide. caption: Photo by Jasper Doest @jasperdoest | An x-ray photo of Flamingo Bob. Bob was rescued by my cousin Odette, who works as a veterinarian on the island of Curaçao. Odette discovered that the flamingo developed an arthritic condition on both of his feet—one of the reasons he couldn't be released back to the wild as he simply wouldn't survive. She now uses the bird for education purposes within Fundashon Dier en Onderwijs Cariben @fdoccuracao, which is why we also had a x-ray made of his beautiful long neck in addition to his feet. With 19 vertebrae, flamingos actually have fewer neck vertebrae than many other long-necked birds. But having fewer vertebrae doesn’t necessarily mean that the neck is shorter; the bones themselves are longer. They are seen  as a series of angles, rather than as a continuous smooth curve. This allows flamingos to bend their neck backward or downward to clean their feathers or search for food—its neck is vital to filtering food from water, as a flamingo often needs to turn its head upside down in the process. Follow @jasperdoest for more images of Flamingo Bob, who is slowly becoming instafamous. #birdrescue #flamingo #xray #flamingobob

caption: Photo by Drew Rush @drewtrush | Snowy Range Scenic Byway, Wyoming. We kept talking about how thankful we were for this place all weekend. Our daughter had met some friends camping earlier in the summer in another spot and we just happened to meet them again here. Serendipity in the mountains, I suppose. So thankful to have a chance to raise my daughter and my son in the woods. Being outside always seems to trigger this response in me, and did you know that the effects of gratitude can be huge? A study titled “Counting Blessings vs. Burdens” in 2003 concluded that keeping a gratitude journal caused participants to report 16% fewer symptoms, 19% more time exercising, 10% less physical pain, 8% more sleep, and 25% increase in sleep quality. Maybe we should all be spending a little more time outside. #nature #beauty #wyoming #gratitude #commonground

caption: Photos by Paul Nicklen @paulnicklen | One of the things that fascinates me most about the ocean is how little we know. So many mysteries and secrets are hidden in the depths of the sea, so many things still to be discovered. Narwhals are sometimes called the unicorns of the sea, and the males are most recognizable by their ivory tusks, a long canine tooth covered in thousands of nerve endings and pores that protrudes from the upper jaw. The recent establishment of the Tuvaijuittuq Marine Protected Area in northern Canada is a huge conservation win for many reasons. Perhaps most important is the prohibition of human activity in the area. This means no commercial fishing. No mining. No oil or gas development. Their absence will mean safe migratory paths for the whales who pass through these waters. Follow me @PaulNicklen for more stories about success in conservation. #TurningTheTide #BornToIce #narwhal #marineprotectedarea

caption: Photos by Pete McBride @pedromcbride | Tuamotu Tale: I spent six weeks on this floating general store—a rusty cargo ship called the Kura Ora. Its crew of 16 giant, tattooed Puamotuan men travel roughly 3,000 miles each month through the Tuamotu archipelago delivering food, alcohol, tobacco, fuel, toys, engines, fish, dried coconut, and passengers (most alive, some deceased, returning for funeral services in Tahiti). Each atoll we reached was unique: some full of fishermen, some famous for black pearl farms, others bristling with kids and dolphins, and one was inhabited by just two people drying copra (coconut). But all the stops had challenging reef crossings—making each delivery by small oar boats a risky adventure. I shot this for @natgeo years ago, but the voices of the line-backer sized crew calling me ‘Petero’ sound like yesterday. For more on water across the world, follow @pedromcbride. #ocean #tuamotus #pacific #pearls #nature

caption: Photo by Brian Skerry @brianskerry | Happy International Whale Shark Day! A snorkeler swims above a large whale shark near the surface in waters off western Australia. The largest fish in the sea, whale sharks are now classified as an endangered species, since their numbers have been reduced by half, according to recent studies. Swimming with whale sharks has long been one of my favorite experiences. They can be massive yet so gentle, moving gracefully and purposefully through the sea. I feel that they are always quite aware of my presence, but rarely give me much thought. It’s as if they are on a long and ancient journey, and I am simply a momentary distraction. Follow @BrianSkerry for more ocean wildlife images and stories! #InternationalWhaleSharkDay

caption: Photo by Nichole Sobecki @nicholesobecki | I met Lowelu Krion on the shores of Lake Turkana, as she waited for her father and brothers to return from retrieving their fishing nets. Sitting together, her mother told me of their life beside the jade sea, and the home it had been for her mother and others, generations back. The harsh terrain surrounding the blue-green waters here ensured that this was the last great African lake mapped by Europeans, and it remains one of East Africa’s most remote regions. The world’s largest permanent desert lake, Turkana has existed for some four million years, but Lowelu’s mother was concerned with the future, not the past. A dam up north and nearby plantations are squeezing the lake and those who survive by fishing from its shores. Many worry its days are numbered. Uncertainty looms for Lowelu and her family, but in the determination of her gaze I felt a small but fierce glimpse of hope. #laketurkana #kenya #water #nicholesobecki

caption: Photo by Natalie Keyssar @nataliekeyssar | In Yalambojoch, Catarina Gomez Lucas makes her family's tortillas every morning. In December her brother Felipe died in U.S. custody after crossing the border with their father. Residents of their region of Huehuetenango are leaving Guatemala for the U.S. in record numbers. “They don’t know how we live,” Catarina says on a chilly February morning, a few days after Felipe’s funeral. We’re sitting on stools in her kitchen, where she’s patting corn dough and slapping the circles onto a stovetop. Smoke fills the room. “People giving these opinions have a better life. They don’t have to leave their families to survive like we do here.” For more on this story, please follow @Nataliekeyssar and read the full piece by @ninasabina24 for @natgeo.

caption: Photo by Cristina Mittermeier @cristinamittermeier | How different would the world be if all our children were raised like the Quechua children? In this photo, a Quechua child holds his llama close. While traveling in Peru, I was fascinated by the strong connection to nature the Quechua people have. Descendants of the Inca Empire, the Quechua live peacefully in the high Andes of Peru and continue to worship Pachamama, the Earth goddess. They believe that if you take care of her, she, in turn, will take care of you. The forest is not just a pile of firewood, and the river is not just there to fill bottles of water. Even the gentle llama is not a beast of burden but family. I'm grateful for the time they shared with me and their teachings. Follow me @cristinamittermeier for more photos that highlight the relationship between ancient traditions and modern practices. #Peru #Nature #ProtectOurPlanet
labels: llama alpaca camelid livestock smile wool

caption:
Photo by Jasper Doest @jasperdoest | Flamingo Bob enjoys a lovely summer evening at a private beach in Curaçao. Now that schools are closed for the summer, his educational duty is reduced to a minimum, and he spends most of his time hanging around the house of my cousin Odette, who is a veterinarian on the island and takes care of Bob, as he can't be released back to the wild because of a chronic foot condition. Odette feels Bob still belongs out in the open, so she regularly takes him to the beach for a swim, which also serves as aqua-therapy for his arthritic feet. Odette also runs the wildlife conservation and education charity @fdoccuracao, for which Bob is an animal ambassador. 
Follow @jasperdoest for more images of Flamingo Bob, who is slowly becoming instafamous. #sunset #flamingo #prettyinpink #flamingobob #curacao

caption: Photo by Ami Vitale @amivitale | A wild elephant herd passes through an area called Loijuk, near Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e) in northern Kenya. Before @r.e.s.c.ue was founded, orphaned elephants had to be transported 240 miles away, and they would be reintroduced in Tsavo National Park, in Kenya's south. There was no chance they would ever encounter their kin again. One of the great benefits @r.e.s.c.u.e offers is that now these elephant calves are raised near where they were rescued and may be able to return to the same herds they were originally separated from. Learn how to get involved by following @amivitale and @r.e.s.c.u.e. @conservationorg @thephotosociety @natgeoimagecollection #protectelephants #elephants #stoppoaching #kenya #worthmorealive

caption: Photo by Paul Nicklen @paulnicklen | Thirty years before divers found bones at the bottom of Las Calaveras, local Maya still collected their drinking water from this cenote. Since then, archaeologists have documented the remains of more than one hundred people found in Las Calaveras. For the ancient Maya, both caves and cenotes were considered mouths that opened into an otherworld. The series of photographs I took for National Geographic are some of the most haunting of my career. They are also some of the most beautiful. The ghostly figure in the distance here is Cristina Mittermeier, illuminated by the light that shines down from the mouth of the cenote. Follow me @PaulNicklen for more images from some of my favorite  assignments. #history #cenotes #diving #caves

caption: Photo by Dina Litovsky @dina_litovsky | Three people walk toward the Temple of Transition at the Burning Man festival in Black Rock City, Nevada. The annual event attended by over 70,000 people and known for its psychedelic dance parties and elaborate art installations, features a different, larger-than-life temple each year. On the last day of Burning Man, the temple is burned to the ground in solemn silence. I've attended the festival over the years, and this magnificent structure from 2011 remains my favorite. caption: Photo by Brian Skerry @brianskerry | A close-up of a mako shark in the waters off New Zealand. Makos are one of the fastest fish in the sea, capable of bursts up to 60mph.  Of all shark species, they have one of the largest brains, relative to body size. They are also an endothermic shark, meaning that they can generate heat within their bodies. This allows them to swim into cooler waters to feed on oily fish, giving them great strength and fueling their powerful muscles. The numbers of makos have declined worldwide due to over fishing and the demand for shark fins. Follow @BrianSkerry to see more sharks and other ocean animals. #makoshark #sharks #savesharks

caption: Photo by Pete McBride @pedromcbride // Sponsored by @BritaUSA // As volunteers from Hawaii Wildlife Fund worked to clean up a southern beach on Hawaii’s Big Island, I swam just inside the surging surf amid a pounding plastic slurry, trying to document the kaleidoscope of convenience before me. At high tide, the tidal pools churned with endless swirls of microplastics—bits and pieces of single-use bottles, cups, and containers—that made their way here to America’s island paradise from around the world. Thanks to volunteers who have removed over 275 tons of plastic waste from this coastline, it looks cleaner than it did a few years ago. The giant bottles and crates are gone. But when you look closer, you quickly realize the entire shore is a matrix of lava, sand, and microplastics. And it will keep coming until we as consumers and business leaders start to change our dependence on single-use plastic. Today, only 9 percent of single-use containers get recycled. The rest of it ends up in rivers, seas, and eventually even paradisiacal beaches like this one. #planetorplastic // @BritaUSA believes everyone deserves cleaner, great-tasting water without the waste of bottles. Last year alone, Brita owners filtered enough water to replace over 10.5 billion single-use plastic water bottles. Learn more at Brita.com.
labels: water sea ocean rock coast shore waste photography wave coastal and oceanic landforms
